{{distinguish|Sara Gula language}} {{Infobox language |name=Kara |nativename=Tar Gula |states=[[Central African Republic]] and [[South Sudan]] |ethnicity=[[Kara people|Kara]] |speakers={{sigfig|13,200|2}} |date=1996 |ref=e18 |familycolor=Nilo-Saharan |fam2=[[Central Sudanic]] |fam3=[[Bongo–Bagirmi languages|Bongo–Bagirmi]] |fam4=[[Kara languages|Kara]] |iso3=kcm |glotto=gula1266 |glottorefname=Gula (Central African Republic) }}
The '''Gula language''', or ''Tar Gula'', of the [[Central African Republic]], commonly known as '''Kara''', is a [[Central Sudanic languages|Central Sudanic language]] or [[dialect cluster]]. The term "Kara" is also attached to numerous ethnic groups of the region and their languages, and so is often ambiguous.
''Ethnologue'' lists ''Gula du Mamoun, Kara'' (of South Sudan) and ''Yamegi'' as synonyms, and ''Molo, Mele, Mot-Mar (Moto-Mara), Sar (Sara), Mere, ''and ''Zura (Koto)'' as dialects.
Sources disagree as to whether Gula shares a [[Kara languages|Kara branch]] with other languages, with proposed Kara languages in one classification reassigned to other branches in other classifications. (See [[Kara languages]].)
